reasoning:
I’m going to start with my first rule: Circle of competence. I’ve spent my life understanding simple, consumer-driven businesses—Coca-Cola, See’s Candies, insurance—and frankly, the inner workings of digital advertising and search algorithms fall outside my wheelhouse. Without solid fundamentals, financials, or reliable valuation data in front of me here, I can’t honestly claim to understand Google’s true economic engine.

That said, from what’s publicly known, Google does possess a wide moat—dominant market share in search, powerful network effects, and huge data advantages that create real switching costs for advertisers. Their management has shown competence: strong free-cash-flow generation, prudent buybacks, and moonshot investments under Alphabet’s umbrella. On the balance sheet front, I’d expect a fortress, though I can’t confirm it with the data you’ve provided.

When it comes to price, I’m a simple soul: ‘‘Price is what you pay; value is what you get.’’ Without an intrinsic value estimate or margin of safety, I can’t say whether today’s price leaves room to sleep well at night. And in my portfolio, I’d sooner buy a wonderful business at a fair price than a fair business at a wonderful price.

Long term, Google’s prospects in AI and cloud look interesting, but the field is changing fast, regulatory headwinds loom, and I see plenty of unknowns. Compared to the straightforward economics of a Coke or a GEICO, this one’s too fuzzy.

So I’ll pass—neither bullish nor bearish—until I understand the story better and see a real margin of safety. I’d rather wait on the sidelines than risk permanent impairment of capital on something outside my circle.
